Christoph Spielmann wrote:

&gt; Hi everybody!
&gt;
&gt; I got two questions for you:
&gt;
&gt; First let&#39;s assume you want to crawl a web-page and
&gt; you want heritrix to pretend to be one of the &quot;big&quot;
&gt; webspiders (GoogleBot e.g.). I know i can change the
&gt; user-agent to something like &lt;user-agent&gt;(+&lt;url&gt;) but
&gt; is the usage of &quot;GoogleBot (+http://x.net) &lt;http://x.net%29&gt; enough to
&gt; pretend that this is Googlebot??

Effectively, yes.  This &#39;user-agent&#39; string is usually how servers would 
distingush agents whether its adding special handling/defenses or when 
designating access rules in robots.txt.

But note, we&#39;d strongly counsel against you posing as someone else&#39;s 
agent.  Because of misconfigurations or because you&#39;re not privvy to 
arrangements made between the target site and agent, there is the danger 
that you could blacken the  name of the robot you&#39;re posing as.  If the 
site only allows crawling by GoogleBot or some other agent, rather than 
pose as GoogleBot, try contacting the webmaster and ask that your 
crawler be allowed access.

&gt;
&gt; Second if you take a look at the crawlorder-file you
&gt; can see something like that:
&gt;
&gt; &lt;newObject name=&quot;robots-honoring-policy&quot;
&gt; class=&quot;org.archive.crawler.datamodel.RobotsHonoringPolicy&quot;&gt;
&gt;       &lt;string name=&quot;type&quot;&gt;classic&lt;/string&gt;
&gt;       &lt;boolean name=&quot;masquerade&quot;&gt;false&lt;/boolean&gt;
&gt;       &lt;text name=&quot;custom-robots&quot;&gt;&lt;/text&gt;
&gt;       &lt;stringList name=&quot;user-agents&quot;&gt;
&gt;       &lt;/stringList&gt;
&gt;     &lt;/newObject&gt;
&gt;
&gt; Can anybody explain me what the idea of this thing
&gt; is??

Take a look at &#39;6.5.1.4. Robots honoring policy&#39; in the user manual: 
http://crawler.archive.org/articles/user_manual.html#settings.  It makes 
a cut at explaining these fields.

Good luck,
